did.abstract: The collection consists of correspondence, production records, business records, photographs, music, artwork, posters, clippings, awards, ephemera, artifacts, sound recordings, and video recordings from just prior to the founding of A & M Records in 1962 to a few years after its sale to Polygram in 1989, while Jerry Moss and Herb Alpert were still affiliated with the label.

bioghist.head: Biographical History
bioghist.p: Founded in 1962 in Los Angeles, California by Jerry Moss and Herb Alpert, A&M Records became America's largest independent record company. Both men were born in 1935, Alpert in Los Angeles and Moss in New York. The two met in the early 1960s, when Alpert was writing and recording songs and Moss was an independent record promoter. Their social acquaintance quickly became a partnership when in 1962 the two formed Carnival Records, based in Alpert's garage. With contributions of $100 from each man, the company released the single "Tell It to the Birds." After discovering later that year that the Carnival name was already in use, Alpert and Moss created the company's new name from the initials of their last names.

A&M Records' first release, the single "The Lonely Bull" by Herb Alpert & The Tijuana Brass, came out in August 1962. It reached number six on the Billboard charts and sold some 700,000 copies. Other best-selling Tijuana Brass albums followed, including "Whipped Cream and Other Delights" and "What Now My Love." Led by the success of the Tijuana Brass, A&M revenue topped $50 million by 1968; by the end of the decade the band had sold some 45 million albums.

A&M's roster featured many of the top pop and rock acts from the 1960s, 1970s, and 1980s, including Bryan Adams, Burt Bacharach, Joan Baez, the Baja Marimba Band, the Captain and Tennille, the Carpenters, Cheech and Chong, Joe Cocker, Peter Frampton, Lani Hall, Janet Jackson, Joe Jackson, Sergio Mendes and Brasil '66, the Neville Brothers, Jeffrey Osborne, The Police, Squeeze, Cat Stevens, Sting, Styx, Supertramp, and the Tubes, among many others. A number of jazz composers and performers were also issued by the label, including Gato Barbieri, Quincy Jones and Paul Winter as well as some late recordings by Chet Baker and Stan Getz.
In 1989 Alpert and Moss sold A&M records to PolyGram Records.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: The collection consists of correspondence, production records, business records, photographs, music, artwork, posters, clippings, awards, ephemera, artifacts, Herb Alpert & The Tijuana Brass clothing, sound recordings, and video recordings.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The collection has been arranged into the following series:

Series 1: Correspondence, 1959-1992 Series 2: Production records, 1965-1988 Series 3: Business records, 1961-2001 Series 4: Photographs, 1960s-1980s Series 5: Music, 1917-1984 Series 6: Artwork, undated Series 7: Posters, 1971-1977 Series 8: Clippings, 1956-1989 Series 9: Awards, 1960-1989 Series 10: Ephemera and artifacts, 1957-1982 Series 11: Herb Alpert & the Tijuana Brass clothing, circa 1960s Series 12: Sound recordings, 1910-1999 Series 13: Video recordings, 1983-1991

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: Herb Alpert's letters received primarily concern his events and performances with the Tijuana Brass; also Alpert's charitable activities, some fan letters, congratulatory telegrams, and thank yous. A few letters or telegrams are from other musicians. The bulk of Alpert's letters sent are copies of thank you letters, most with original letters received attached.

Jerry Moss's correspondence mostly deals with A&M artists and the label's business activities, including with affiliates and divisions. Gil Friesen's correspondence, president of A&M from 1977-1990, concerns A&M's business, especially legal matters, and Herb Alpert & the Tijuana Brass television specials. Sal Monte's letters, road manager for Herb Alpert & the Tijuana Brass, detail travel and tour arrangements for the band.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: Includes two letters from Chet Baker, November 12, 1968 (postmark date) and April 29, 1969 (both in box 1).

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: Includes letters to other staff, to A & M Records generally, or unknown recipients.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: Framed telegrams and other items from Hubert Humphrey, Mace Neufeld, and the White House.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: The bulk of this series consists of tour itineraries for Herb Alpert and the Tijuana Brass; also present are forms, receipts, equipment lists, and seating charts. In addition, there are two folders of pre-prepared stage banter for the group. A small amount of tour material is present for the Baja Marimba Band, Sergio Mendes and Brasil '66, and a few other A&M artists.

Material is most likely from the files of Herb Alpert & the Tijuana Brass's Road Manager Sal Monte or Assistant Road Manager Bill Earl. See also Sal Monte's correspondence in box 7 for additional tour-related material.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: Rondor Music records are primarily management accounts. The bulk of Almo/Irving material is catalogs.

Rondor Music, Almo Music Corp, and Irving Music Inc. were all music publishing groups established by Herb Alpert and Jerry Moss in 1962. Almo Music Corp. was formally incorporated on October 5, 1962. Irving Music. Inc. was brought into the Alpert and Moss partnership by Moss.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: Primarily includes various contracts and agreements for appearances and music publishing, mostly for Herb Alpert & the Tijuana Brass. There are no recording contracts for A&M artists present.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: Includes A&M staff bios and lists, some benefits information, and programs relating to staff meetings and events.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: Includes several royalty statements for Herb Alpert (1961-1970), and a small amount of various invoices, rate schedules, earnings projections, salary information, and a stock report (1988). Also included is an early A&M checkbook with stubs from 1962-1963 and a ledger from 1957, possibly for Alpert's songwriting venture for Keen Records.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: Some artist biographies and press releases / kits contain publicity photos. Artists include Herb Alpert & the Tijuana Brass, Sergio Mendes & Brasil '66, Baja Marimba Band, the Carpenters, Humble Pie, Carole King, Joan Baez, and others.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: This subseries contains various reports for the National Association of Recording Merchandisers, Shelter Records, the Alpert Family Foundation, the Los Angeles Olympic Organizing Committee, and promotional reports and catalogs of non-A&M artists.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: Includes programs for tribute events for Herb Alpert and Jerry Moss.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: Images primarily depict Alpert with other entertainment or public figures, including Jerry Lewis, Queen Elizabeth, Lyndon Johnson, Sergio Mendes, Eddie Fisher, and Steve Allen. Oversize photographs in box 21 also include Harry Belafonte and Dizzy Gillespie. Also present are snapshots of Alpert receiving a star on the Walk of Fame (box 18), as well as Herb Alpert & the Tijuana Brass's trip to Tijuana (box 18, folder 6).

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: Photographs of various performances, plus numerous snapshots of the group on tour. Includes a color photograph of a performance at the White House, 1967 (box 21, folder 6).

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: Includes many photographs of Whipped Cream & Other Delights album cover recreations.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: Photographs of Alpert's childhood home, and high school. (Photograph of Alpert's mother with Jerry Moss's mother: box 168, folder 1.)

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: Includes photographs of the Baja Marimba Band, Sergio Mendes & Brasil '66, Lani Hall (solo and with Brasil '66), Chuck Mangione, Joan Armatrading, Quincy Jones, Chris Montez, Atlantic Starr, Gino Vanelli, Tim Curry, Sister Janet Mead, Supertramp, Billy Preston, Pablo Cruz, Claudine Longet, the Dickies, and others. Oversize photographs include Rita Coolidge and Burt Bacharach (box 22, folder 5).

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: Includes color photograph of the group's White House performance, 1966; autographed by President Lyndon Johnson and Lady Bird Johnson (box 22, folder 4).

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: Includes numerous black and white snapshots of a recording session of the band, as well as of Lanu Hall solo (box 22).

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: Photographs of Jerry Moss, Herb Alpert, Gil Friesen, Harold Childs, and other A&M executives and staff, some of which include A&M artists including Peter Frampton and Styx. box 168, folder 3; the Carpenters, the Police, Quincy Jones, George Harrison box 20, folder 1. Also present are shots of the A&M lot and offices on La Brea Avenue in Hollywood and of the A&M recording studio. Includes some contact sheets and negatives.
Photograph of Jerry Moss's and Herb Alpert's mothers is located in Subseries 1 (box 168, folder 1).
Includes an oversize mounted photo of Alpert, Moss, and Friesen (box 23).
